[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m (2) **Support-decision-record journal, longitudinal store, sensitive-disclosure store, crisis-event record, conversation log, and tool-call ledger accumulate multi-year-longitudinal mental-health-PHI-rich free-text outside archive-reference pattern, with recipe-distinct mental-health-PHI-as-most-sensitive-PHI-class and 42-CFR-Part-2-substance-use-treatment-records and state-specific-mental-health-record-statutes-exceeding-HIPAA-baseline and FDA-SaMD-post-market-obligations and mandatory-reporting-disclosure-as-additionally-sensitive amplifications.** Same chapter pattern as 11.4, 11.5, 11.6, and 11.7 with recipe-distinct life-safety-acute extensions. The Step 6 persist_support_artifacts decision-record write includes the full decision_payload, full citations, full active-version stamps. The Step 6C sensitive-disclosure-record write includes the disclosure_excerpt (with the recipe-distinct minimal-context-not-full-transcript framing as partial credit). The crisis-event-record write at Step 3A includes the full screening_result. The longitudinal-store updates at Step 6D accumulate years of mental-health-conversation history, sensitive disclosures, and crisis-history flags. The recipe-distinct dimensions include the longitudinal-store-as-most-sensitive-clinical-record framing (mental-health PHI is the most sensitive PHI class with state-specific privacy protections that exceed HIPAA baseline in many states; 42 CFR Part 2 applies for substance-use treatment data with stricter consent and disclosure rules; psychotherapy-notes have additional HIPAA Privacy Rule protections), the per-record-class retention floor reconciliation covering the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, state-specific mental-health-record retention rules per state of patient residence (which often exceed general medical-record rules), 42 CFR Part 2 retention for substance-use treatment data where applicable, FDA SaMD post-market obligations, and litigation-hold obligations (mental-health-bot deployment with a patient-suicide outcome is a foreseeable litigation-hold scenario per the recipe's own malpractice-exposure framing). The recipe contains an explicit `<!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S3 (HIGH) -->` marker anticipating this finding.
