[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** Same chapter pattern as 11.4, 11.5, 11.6, and 11.7 with recipe-distinct mental-health-PHI-as-most-sensitive-class, 42-CFR-Part-2-substance-use-treatment-records, state-specific-mental-health-privacy-statutes-exceeding-HIPAA, FDA-SaMD-post-market, and mandatory-reporting-disclosure-as-additionally-sensitive amplifications. The recipe correctly elevates the longitudinal store and the sensitive-disclosure store as separately-governed record classes. Despite this elevation, the architecture pattern, the diagram, and the pseudocode treat the longitudinal-store, decision-record-journal, crisis-event-record, sensitive-disclosure-store, conversation-log, and tool-call-ledger writes as embedding rather than referencing the per-conversation and per-event content. Recipe-acute and life-safety-acute amplification because:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **Mental-health PHI is the most sensitive PHI class.** The longitudinal store accumulates conversation history, sensitive disclosures (intimate-partner violence, substance-use, eating-disorder behavior, trauma, child-abuse-as-survivor or as-witness, suicidality across years), psychiatric diagnoses, psychiatric medications, safety-plan content, and crisis-history flags over years. State medical-records retention obligations apply alongside HIPAA's six-year minimum (per-state mental-health-record retention rules vary; many states require 7-10+ years for mental-health records; some states require lifetime retention for psychiatric inpatient records). FDA SaMD post-market obligations may extend retention further. The architecture should specify the per-state and per-FDA-SaMD retention floor reconciliation and the per-record-class retention regime distinct from the audit-archive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **42 CFR Part 2 applies for substance-use treatment information** with stricter consent and disclosure rules than HIPAA. The recipe's prose correctly notes this. The architecture should specify the substance-use-treatment-information-as-additionally-protected discipline (any conversation content discussing substance-use treatment receives 42 CFR Part 2 treatment with additional consent for any disclosure including to other treating clinicians; separate access-control surface; per-disclosure-policy version stamping).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **State-specific mental-health-record statutes exceed HIPAA baseline in many states.** California (LPS Act, Confidentiality of Medical Information Act), New York (Mental Hygiene Law Article 33), Illinois (Mental Health and Developmental Disabilities Confidentiality Act), Massachusetts (Mental Health Records Privacy), and others have specific protections for mental-health records that exceed HIPAA's baseline including stricter access controls, stricter consent for disclosure to other treating clinicians, and stricter patient-access rights. The architecture should specify the per-state regulatory configuration with explicit per-state retention, access-control, consent, and disclosure-accounting variations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **Psychotherapy notes have additional HIPAA Privacy Rule protections.** The architecture should specify whether the bot's conversation log constitutes psychotherapy notes under HIPAA (this is a clinical-and-legal determination per institutional policy), and where it does or could, the additional-protection discipline (more restrictive access, more restrictive disclosure-to-other-treating-clinicians).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Mandatory-reporting-relevant disclosures are recipe-distinct additionally-sensitive content.** Disclosures of child abuse, elder abuse, intimate-partner violence in some states, and certain mental-health crisis types trigger statutory reporting obligations. The recipe correctly routes these to the sensitive-disclosure store with separately-managed KMS key (good, partial credit). The architecture should specify the mandatory-reporting-disclosure handling as state-specific (per-state mandatory-reporter category and routing target) with per-disclosure-policy version stamping and per-state-specific reporting-workflow integration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   6. **The patient's right to access their longitudinal record per HIPAA and (per state and contract) right to request deletion is not architecturally elevated.** Patients have HIPAA right-of-access to most of their PHI; mental-health records have specific access considerations. Some states have specific deletion-right provisions. The architecture should specify the patient-right-of-access workflow (the patient can review their longitudinal store contents per HIPAA), the state-and-contract-permitted deletion workflow, and the deletion-vs-retention-conflict resolution (FDA SaMD post-market obligations and certain state mental-health-record laws may prohibit deletion of certain record classes; mandatory-reporting-relevant disclosures may have specific retention obligations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   7. **The conversation log accumulating across years is dense mental-health PHI plus may include sensitive disclosures.** The recipe's prose elevates "the conversation history accumulates across years" as architectural primitive. The architecture should specify the per-record-class retention reconciliation (audit-archive retention vs support-decision-record-journal retention vs longitudinal-store retention vs conversation-log retention vs sensitive-disclosure-archive retention vs crisis-event-record retention vs tool-call-ledger retention may differ; mental-health institutional policy may treat the conversation log as part of the mental-health record while general medical institutions treat audit pipeline differently).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   8. **Liability-driven litigation-hold scenarios are recipe-distinct.** The recipe correctly elevates "a bot that fails a crisis screen and a patient is subsequently harmed is a foreseeable liability exposure." The architecture should specify the litigation-hold workflow with crisis-event-record and support-decision-record-journal preservation discipline beyond the standard retention floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Adopt the archive-reference discipline uniformly across the longitudinal store, the support-decision-record journal, the sensitive-disclosure store, the crisis-event record, the conversation log, and the tool-call ledger on the real-time hot path:
